"Zerbini S., Baker T., Negusini M., Plag H.-P., Romagnoli C.","Height variations and secular changes in sea level",1998,"Journal of Geodynamics","25","3-4",,"241","262",,,10.1016/S0264-3707(97)00038-0,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0032075942&partnerID=40&md5=b86f76cbe30b2d76c2a0811ce0c60fb6","Dipartimento di Fisica, Settore di Geofisica, Università di Bologna, Bologna, Italy; Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory, Birkenhead, United Kingdom; Statens Kartverk, Geodetic Division, Honefoss, Norway; Dipto. di Scienze Mineralogiche, Università di Bologna, Bologna, Italy","Zerbini, S., Dipartimento di Fisica, Settore di Geofisica, Università di Bologna, Bologna, Italy; Baker, T., Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory, Birkenhead, United Kingdom; Negusini, M., Dipartimento di Fisica, Settore di Geofisica, Università di Bologna, Bologna, Italy; Plag, H.-P., Statens Kartverk, Geodetic Division, Honefoss, Norway; Romagnoli, C., Dipto. di Scienze Mineralogiche, Università di Bologna, Bologna, Italy","The problem of understanding, assessing and quantifying the causes of sea-level changes has received increased attention during the past several years, in particular in connection with predictions regarding a rise in the gloval mean sea level due to global warming. the impact aspect of sea-level rise is of particular concern for many coastal areas in densely populated regions of the world. the present availability of space geodetic techniques providing high-accuracy measurements of station positions and of their time variations makes it possible to separate vertical crustal movements and absolute sea-level fluctuations. Gravimetric methods play an important role in the assessment of sea-level variations by providing completely independent measuements of vertical crustal movements. Satellite altimetry now enables the measurement of the spatial variability of sea level. Geological observations can infer former sea levels which are important to understand the present trends. This paper addresses the study of height variations and secular changes in sea level by discussing the most interesting questions and issues, by presenting the current understanding of the phenomena involved, and finally by illustrating the measuring and modeling techniques to be adopted for a comprehensive approach to the problem.",,"satellite altimetry; sea level change; space geodesy",,,,,,"Baker, T.F., Absolute sea-level measurements, climate change and vertical crustal movements (1993) Global and Planetary Change, 8, pp. 149-159; Baker, T.F., Cerutti, G., Corrado, G., Kahle, H.-G., Marson, I., Müller, M., Paradissis, D., Zerbini, S., Sea-level fluctuations: Geophysical interpretation and environmental impact (SELF) (1995) Climate Change and Impacts, pp. 323-338. , ed I. Troen. Proceedings of the symposium held in Copenhagen, Denmark, Sept. 6-10, 1993. European Commission, Science Research Development, EUR 15921 EN; Barlier, F., Boucher, C., Seeger, H., Willis, P., Wilson, P., Project for a GPS campaign in the Western Mediterrean (1990) 4th Symposium on Geodesy in Africa, , Tunis, May 21-27, 1990; Berger, A.L., Long-term variation of the earth's orbital elements (1977) Celestial Mechanics, 15, pp. 53-74; Blewitt, G., The global positioning system (1994) Report of the Surrey Workshop of the IAPSO Tide Gauge Bench Mark Fixing Committee, pp. 17-26. , ed W. E. Carter. Deacon Laboratory, Godalming, Surrey, United Kingdom. 13-15 December 1993, NOAA Technical Report NOSOES0006; Bloom, A.L., Yonekura, N., Coastal terraces generated by sea-level change and tectonic uplift (1985) Models in Geomorphology, pp. 139-154. , ed. M. J. Woldenberg. Allen and Unwin, Winchester, MA; Burke, K., Francis, P., Wells, G., Importance of the geologic record in understanding global change (1990) Global and Planetary Change, 89, pp. 193-204; Carter, W.E., (1994) Report of the Surrey Workshop of the IAPSO Tide Gauge Bench Mark Fixing Committee, , Deacon Laboratory, Godalming, Surrey, U